llette, Anna / Wallette, Anna -- tII: 59 Balto-Finnic Perspectives / rDuBois, Thomas A. -- tPower: Envisioning the northern past -- tII: 60 Canadian Perspectives / rWallace, Birgitta -- tII: 61 U.S. Perspectives / rMitchell, Stephen A. -- tII: 62 North American Perspectives - Suggested Runic Monuments / rWilliams, Henrik -- tII: 63 Irish Perspectives / rNagy, Joseph Falaky -- tII: 64 British Perspectives / rCole, Richard -- tII: 65 The Northern Isles / rMitchell, Stephen A. -- tII: 66 French Perspectives / rStahl, Pierre-Brice -- tII: 67 German Perspectives / rScheel, Roland -- tII: 68 Polish Perspectives / rMorawiec, Jakub -- tII: 69 Russian Perspectives / rSchmid, Ulrich -- tII: 70 Russian Perspectives - Viking / rDavidková, Barbora -- tPart III: Texts and Images -- tEinleitung -- tRemembering the Past and Foreseeing the Future: Mnemonic genres and classical Old Norse memory texts -- t Media of Memory and Forgetting: Oral and written transmission of memories in prologues and colophones -- tMedia of Memory and Forgetting: Figures of remembering and forgetting -- t Memory in Action: Memory strategies and memory scenes in sagas, poetry, laws, and theological and historical texts -- tRunic Inscriptions -- tColour Plates -- tSelect Bibliography of Pre-Modern Nordic Memory Studies -- tContributors -- t Index  aIn recent years, the field of Memory Studies has emerged as a key approach in the Humanities and Social Sciences, and has increasingly shown its ability to open new windows on Nordic Studies as well. The entries in this book document the work-to-date of this approach on the pre-modern Nordic world (mainly the Viking Age and the Middle Ages, but including as well both earlier and later periods). Given that Memory Studies is an ever expanding critical strategy, the approximately eighty contributors in this volume also discuss the potential for future research in this area. Topics covered range from texts to performance to visual and other aspects of material culture, all approached from within an interdisciplinary framework. International specialists, coming from such relevant fields as archaeology, mythology, history of religion, folklore, history, law, art, literature, philology, language, and mediality, offer assessments on the relevance of Memory Studies to their disciplines and show it at work in case studies. Finally, this handbook demonstrates the various levels of culture where memory had a critical impact in the pre-modern North and how deeply embedded the role of memory is in the material itself.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 4aAltnordische Literatur. 4aMedialität. 4aOld Norse literature. 4aScandinavia. 4aSkandinavien. 4amediality. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Reference.2bisacsh1 aGlauser, Jürg, eeditor.1 aHermann, Pernille, eeditor.1 aMitchell, Stephen A., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104314830 cprintz978311044020140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110431360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110431360.jpg  a978-3-11-060418-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-061685-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishb2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEB